The function named `sequence_classifier` makes use of the `all()` function, which is a built-in function in Python that returns True if all items in an iterable are true, otherwise, it returns False. Furthermore, list comprehensions have been used to navigate through the elements and compare their values effectively.

The algorithm checks for the following sequence types in order: constant, strictly increasing, not decreasing, strictly decreasing, not increasing, and unordered. Each check corresponds to a certain code per the specifications of your kata. If none of the conditions for ordered lists are met, the function defaults to returning code `0` for unordered lists.

It's important to highlight that this function runs in linear time, meaning its runtime complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the array. Moreover, the function adheres to the functional programming paradigm, as it does not modify the input array and solely returns the result based on evaluations.

The following code is the implementation of the aforementioned logic and will classify the input series into one of the predefined sequence types, returning the corresponding code.
```python
def sequence_classifier(arr):
	if all((arr[i] == arr[i + 1] for i in range(len(arr) - 1))):
		return 5
	if all((arr[i] < arr[i + 1] for i in range(len(arr) - 1))):
		return 1
	if all((arr[i] <= arr[i + 1] for i in range(len(arr) - 1))):
		return 2
	if all((arr[i] > arr[i + 1] for i in range(len(arr) - 1))):
